You can generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document using the `tableofcontents` command from the `tocloft` package (not `toc` package, which is deprecated). Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{report} % or book, article, etc.

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % Include this command to generate the TOC

\chapter{Introduction}
\section{This is section 1}
\subsection{This is subsection 1.1}

\chapter{Methods}
\section{Section 2}
\subsection{Subsection 2.1}
\subsection{Subsection 2.2}

% ... rest of your document ...

\end{document}
```

When you run this document through LaTeX (e.g., using `pdflatex` or `xelatex`), it will generate a table of contents at the beginning of the document, listing all the headings (chapters, sections, and subsections) with their corresponding page numbers.

Note that the `report` document class is used here, which is suitable for documents with a structured layout, such as reports or theses. If you're using a different class (e.g., `article`), the TOC will still be generated, but it might not be as comprehensive.

If you want to customize the appearance of the TOC, you can use packages like `tocloft` or `tocstyle` to modify the formatting, spacing, and layout of the table of contents.

